explanation:
Needed symbols and why they are required for a dead-code (MISRA) analysis of OS_SocketConnect:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - Determines how a NULL Addr is handled (e.g. early return, assertion, abort). This affects reachability of the rest of the function and whether subsequent code can be considered dead.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - Controls whether the main body executes (return_code and token). Its return values and side-effects determine reachability of the branches and whether later operations are executed.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease
  - Called unconditionally on the token when ObjectIdGetById succeeded. Its side-effects (resource release) affect program behaviour; whether it is required or removable factors into dead-code analysis.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Maps the token to the stream pointer. Understanding how this mapping works is necessary to know if the obtained pointer is valid and whether writing to it has program effects.

- OS_stream_table
  - The global table used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to reason about what stream points to and whether updates to stream entries have observable effects elsewhere.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t
  - The structure type for stream; required to know the meanings of socket_domain, socket_type and stream_state and whether modifying stream->stream_state can affect program behaviour.

- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID
  - Used in the domain check; its definition determines whether that branch can be true and thus whether the error-assignment is reachable.

- OS_SocketType_STREAM
  - Used in the type check; needed to determine reachability of the incorrect-state branch for stream sockets.

- OS_STREAM_STATE_CONNECTED
  - Used to test if the stream is already connected; crucial for reachability of the incorrect-state branch.

- OS_STREAM_STATE_READABLE
  - One of the flags ORed into stream_state on success; needed to decide whether that write has observable effect.

- OS_STREAM_STATE_WRITABLE
  - Same as above; needed to judge whether the assignment after a successful connect is meaningful.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_TYPE
  - Error constant assigned when domain is invalid; required to know if that assignment is reachable and used by callers.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE
  - Error constant assigned when socket already connected; needed to evaluate reachability and whether the assignment affects program behaviour.

- OS_SocketConnect_Impl
  - Performs the actual connect and returns status. Its semantics and side-effects determine whether the following update to stream->stream_state is necessary (i.e. whether that update is dead).

- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE
  - Passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; influences how the object lookup behaves (locking) and thus may affect whether ObjectIdGetById can succeed.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE
  - The object type passed to ObjectIdGetById; affects whether the lookup succeeds and thus reachability of subsequent code.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The success return code constant used in branches; needed to determine which branches execute and whether assignments are dead.

- osal_id_t
  - Type of sock_id; knowing if it can alias or represent special values may affect reachability and semantics of the lookup call.

- OS_SockAddr_t
  - Type of Addr pointer; necessary because OS_CHECK_POINTER and OS_SocketConnect_Impl behavior may depend on Addr semantics and whether its use has side-effects.

Rationale summary: To decide if any operations in OS_SocketConnect are dead (removable without changing program behaviour) one must know which branches are reachable and whether operations (notably mapping to the stream and modifying stream->stream_state, plus token release) have observable side-effects. The symbols above define the control-flow conditions, the object mapping, the structure and flags modified, and the called implementation that may also produce side-effects; all are required to make a sound dead-code determination.
